OL,3,CMet Office warns of rise in extreme UK
OL,4,Cweather, as 2023 second hottest year
OL,5,Cever
OL,7,F"The attribution studies help to
OL,8,Funderstand how human activities, such
OL,9,Fas burning fossil fuels, are making
OL,10,Fthese extreme events much more likely
OL,11,Fto happen as our climate continues to
OL,12,Fchange."
OL,14,FForecasters say the frequency of these
OL,15,Fextremes will put added pressure on
OL,16,Fhealth services and infrastructure.
OL,17,FWhat's more, they say last year's
OL,18,Fextremes will become the new norm.
